SIMPLE: wipe
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wipe
<hw>Wipe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Sw. <ets>vipa</ets>,
Dan. <ets>vibe</ets>, the lapwing.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The
lapwing.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wipe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wipe
<hw>Wipe</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wiped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wiping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>vipen</ets>, AS.
<ets>w⟦imac⟧pian</ets>; cf. LG. <ets>wiep</ets> a wisp of straw, Sw.
<ets>vepa</ets> to wrap up, to cuddle one's self up, <ets>vepa</ets> a
blanket; perhaps akin to E. <ets>whip</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To rub with something soft for cleaning; to clean or
dry by rubbing; <as>as, to <ex>wipe</ex> the hands or face with a
towel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let me <qex>wipe</qex> thy face.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>wipe</qex> Jerusalem as a man <qex>wipeth</qex> a
dish, <qex>wiping</qex> it, and turning it upside down.</q> <rj><qau>2
Kings xxi. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To remove by rubbing; to rub off; to obliterate; --
usually followed by <xex>away</xex>, <xex>off</xex> or <xex>out</xex>.
Also used figuratively.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>wipe</xex> out our
ingratitude.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some natural tears they dropped, but <qex>wiped</qex> them
soon.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cheat; to defraud; to trick; -- usually followed
by <xex>out</xex>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If they by coveyne [covin] or gile be <qex>wiped</qex> beside
their goods.</q> <rj><qau>Robynson (More's Utopia)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To wipe a joint</b></col> <fld>(Plumbing)</fld>, <cd>to
make a joint, as between pieces of lead pipe, by surrounding the
junction with a mass of solder, applied in a plastic condition by means
of a rag with which the solder is shaped by rubbing.</cd> -- <col><b>To
wipe the nose of</b></col>, <cd>to cheat.</cd> <mark>[Old
Slang]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wipe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wipe
<hw>Wipe</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Act of rubbing, esp. in
order to clean.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A blow; a stroke; a hit; a swipe.</def>
<mark>[Low]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A gibe; a jeer; a severe sarcasm.</def>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A handkerchief.</def> <mark>[Thieves' Cant or
Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Stain; brand.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Slavish <xex>wipe</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wiper</ent>⟦br⟧
